We need to find the value of \( c \) when the area of \( \mathcal{Q} \) is maximized and express \( c \) as \( \sqrt{m} \). 1. **Roots of the Quadratic Equation**: - The roots \( z_1 \) and \( z_2 \) are complex conjugates: \( z_1 = \sqrt{10} e^{i\theta} \) and \( z_2 = \sqrt{10} e^{-i\theta} \). - Their reciprocals are \( \frac{1}{z_1} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} e^{-i\theta} \) and \( \frac{1}{z_2} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} e^{i\theta} \). 2. **Coordinates of Vertices**: - \( z_1 \): \( (\sqrt{10} \cos \theta, \sqrt{10} \sin \theta) \) - \( z_2 \): \( (\sqrt{10} \cos \theta, -\sqrt{10} \sin \theta) \) - \( \frac{1}{z_1} \): \( \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} \cos \theta, -\frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} \sin \theta \right) \) - \( \frac{1}{z_2} \): \( \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} \cos \theta, \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} \sin \theta \right) \) 3. **Area Calculation Using Shoelace Formula**: - The area is calculated using the coordinates of the vertices and the shoelace formula. - The area is found to be \( \frac{81}{20} |\sin(2\theta)| \). 4. **Maximizing the Area**: - The maximum area occurs when \( |\sin(2\theta)| = 1 \), i.e., \( 2\theta = \frac{\pi}{2} \) or \( \frac{3\pi}{2} \). - This corresponds to \( \theta = \frac{\pi}{4} \) or \( \frac{3\pi}{4} \). 5. **Value of \( c \)**: - When \( \theta = \frac{\pi}{4} \), the real part of \( z_1 \) is \( \sqrt{5} \). - The sum \( c = z_1 + z_2 = 2\sqrt{5} \), so \( c = \sqrt{20} \). Thus, the value of \( m \) when \( c = \sqrt{m} \) is \(\boxed{20}\).
